<TITLE>Book recounts battles for Japanese-held islands</TITLE>


<TEXT>
Author: James D. Hornfischer 
   
Title: "The Fleet at Flood Tide" 
   
Publisher: Bantam Books, <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DATE" value="2016">2016</TIMEX3>, hardcover. 503 pp. of text including charts and maps, 48 pp. BW photos 
   
Naval historian James D. Hornfischers subjects are the battles of the U.S. Navy on and around the Japanese-held islands in the Pacific in <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="DATE" value="1944">1944</TIMEX3> and <TIMEX3 tid="t3" type="DATE" value="1945">1945</TIMEX3>, and the enormous buildup of ships, planes and amphibious craft right up to the end of the <EVENT eid="e1" class="OCCURRENCE">war</EVENT> on <TIMEX3 tid="t4" type="DATE" value="1945-09-02">Sept. 2, 1945</TIMEX3>. The subtitle of "The Fleet at Flood Tide" is "America at Total War in the Pacific, 1944-1945." 
   
A flood tide it was, with the <EVENT eid="e2" class="OCCURRENCE">construction</EVENT> through <TIMEX3 tid="t5" type="DATE" value="1944">the end of 1944</TIMEX3> of 24 aircraft carriers, eight battleships, 34 cruisers, 100 escort carriers, 1,117 auxiliaries, 293 destroyers, 503 destroyer escorts, 167 submarines, 2,489 patrol and mine craft, and 68,737 landing craft, plus the planes, ammunition and supplies and all the sailors, Marines and Coast Guard men to man and <EVENT eid="e3" class="OCCURRENCE">fight</EVENT> them. Total war indeed. 
   
While the Army under Gen. Douglas MacArthur <EVENT eid="e4" class="OCCURRENCE">supported</EVENT> by the Seventh Fleet <EVENT eid="e5" class="OCCURRENCE">took</EVENT> the war to the Japanese through the Philippines, Hornfischers main emphasis is the Central Islands campaigns of the Third Fleet <EVENT eid="e6" class="OCCURRENCE">commanded</EVENT> by Admiral William F. Halsey and the Fifth Fleet commanded by Admiral Raymond A. Spruance. I <EVENT eid="e7" class="OCCURRENCE">read</EVENT> a lot of military history, but it <EVENT eid="e8" class="OCCURRENCE">took</EVENT> me a long time to <EVENT eid="e9" class="OCCURRENCE">figure</EVENT> out that these were not separate fleets, but one fleet with <EVENT eid="e10" class="OCCURRENCE">alternating</EVENT> commanders. 
   
In early <TIMEX3 tid="t6" type="DATE" value="2017-05">May</TIMEX3> (Admiral) King and (Admiral) Nimitz <EVENT eid="e11" class="OCCURRENCE">met</EVENT> in San Francisco and <EVENT eid="e12" class="OCCURRENCE">devised</EVENT> a scheme of command whereby Spruance and Halsey would alternate as task force commanders, with (Rear Admiral) Mitscher and Rear Admiral John McCain as their respective <EVENT eid="e13" class="OCCURRENCE">underlings</EVENT> in command of the fast carrier task force. The <EVENT eid="e14" class="OCCURRENCE">rotation</EVENT> of Halsey and Spruance would <EVENT eid="e15" class="OCCURRENCE">ensure</EVENT> an ongoing study in contrasts along the doctrinal divide. When Spruance and Mitscher had command, their forces would be known as the Fifth Fleet and Task Force 58. When Halsey and McCain <EVENT eid="e16" class="OCCURRENCE">took</EVENT> over  the names would <EVENT eid="e17" class="OCCURRENCE">change</EVENT> to Third Fleet and Task Force 38. 
   
The doctrinal divide was that Spruance <EVENT eid="e18" class="OCCURRENCE">used</EVENT> the carriers to <EVENT eid="e19" class="OCCURRENCE">protect</EVENT> the landing forces, while Halsey <EVENT eid="e20" class="OCCURRENCE">used</EVENT> them to <EVENT eid="e21" class="OCCURRENCE">pursue</EVENT> Japanese carriers. Spruances use of the carriers <EVENT eid="e22" class="OCCURRENCE">protected</EVENT> the <EVENT eid="e23" class="OCCURRENCE">landing</EVENT> in the Marianas chain of the islands of Guam, Saipan and Tinian. Halsey <EVENT eid="e24" class="OCCURRENCE">sent</EVENT> the carriers after Japanese carriers <EVENT eid="e25" class="OCCURRENCE">leaving</EVENT> the landing at Leyte in the Philippines unprotected <EVENT eid="e26" class="I_ACTION">allowing</EVENT> destroyer escorts and escort carriers to be <EVENT eid="e27" class="OCCURRENCE">destroyed</EVENT> when Japanese battleships <EVENT eid="e28" class="OCCURRENCE">came</EVENT> through a passage between islands <EVENT eid="e29" class="OCCURRENCE">left</EVENT> unprotected by Halseys Third Fleet. Heroically the sacrifices of four destroyer escorts and two escort carriers <EVENT eid="e30" class="OCCURRENCE">caused</EVENT> the Japanese to <EVENT eid="e31" class="OCCURRENCE">turn</EVENT> back before they <EVENT eid="e32" class="OCCURRENCE">got</EVENT> in among the landing forces. 
   
Hornfischer does not <EVENT eid="e33" class="OCCURRENCE">disguise</EVENT> his <EVENT eid="e34" class="OCCURRENCE">admiration</EVENT> for Spruance, who was not given a fifth star as a fleet admiral while Halsey <EVENT eid="e35" class="OCCURRENCE">received</EVENT> one. Hornfischer extensively covers Spruance and only has brief passages concerning Halsey and his battles. He writes of how the tenacious Japanese defense, literally to the death, of Iwo Jima and Okinawa convinced planners the <EVENT eid="e36" class="OCCURRENCE">invasion</EVENT> of Japan would be a costly and deadly <EVENT eid="e37" class="OCCURRENCE">undertaking</EVENT>. Everyone was <EVENT eid="e38" class="OCCURRENCE">relieved</EVENT> in <TIMEX3 tid="t7" type="DATE" value="1944">1944</TIMEX3> when the atomic bombs <EVENT eid="e39" class="OCCURRENCE">dropped</EVENT> on Hiroshima and Nagasaki on <TIMEX3 tid="t8" type="DATE" value="2017-08-06">Aug. 6</TIMEX3> and 9, respectively, <EVENT eid="e40" class="REPORTING">ended</EVENT> the <EVENT eid="e41" class="OCCURRENCE">war</EVENT>. 
   
Hornfischer praises MacArthurs control over post-war Japan, a nation that essentially <EVENT eid="e42" class="OCCURRENCE">switched</EVENT> from vicious war-making to acceptance of defeat and cooperation as the Americans <EVENT eid="e43" class="OCCURRENCE">provided</EVENT> food and assistance to a defeated people. The last two chapters are a good narrative of the post-war environment in Japan. There will never again be a navy with this many ships! 
   
Bob Wefald is a retired North Dakota State District Court Judge. Wefald <EVENT eid="e44" class="OCCURRENCE">became</EVENT> a <EVENT eid="e45" class="STATE">lawyer</EVENT> in <TIMEX3 tid="t9" type="DATE" value="1970">1970</TIMEX3>. His career includes <TIMEX3 tid="t10" type="DURATION" value="P4Y">four years</TIMEX3> as attorney general, more <TIMEX3 tid="t11" type="DURATION" value="P23Y">than 23 years</TIMEX3> in private practice in Bismarck and <TIMEX3 tid="t12" type="DURATION" value="P12Y">12 years</TIMEX3> as a judge. He <EVENT eid="e46" class="OCCURRENCE">served</EVENT> as an officer in the Navy for <TIMEX3 tid="t13" type="DURATION" value="P3Y">three years</TIMEX3> of active duty plus <TIMEX3 tid="t14" type="DURATION" value="P24Y">24 years</TIMEX3> in the Navy Reserve.
</TEXT>


